'''Aisyt''' ('''Aysyt''', '''Ajsyt''' or '''Ajyhyt'''; '''{{lang-sah|Айыыһыт}}''' ''Ayııhıt'') is a fertility deity of the [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] [[Yakuts|Yakut]] people from the [[Lena River]] region of [[Siberia]]. The name means "birthgiver" and may also be called the "Mother of Cradles".<ref name="Loar2010">{{cite book|author=Julie Loar|title=Goddesses for Every Day: Exploring the Wisdom and Power of the Divine Feminine Around the World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OturV0aQa-IC&pg=RA1-PA8|accessdate=3 January 2012|date=1 December 2010|publisher=New World Library|isbn=978-1-57731-950-4|page=1}}</ref> Her full name is given as '''Ajysyt-ijaksit-khotan''', meaning "Birthgiving nourishing mother".{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} Aisyt brings the soul from heaven at the birth of a baby and records each one in the Golden Book of Fate and daughter of [[Yer Tanrı]].

==Role==
Ajysyt was responsible for conducting the [[Soul (spirit)|soul]] of a newborn child to its birth and attended every birth. Women would [[channeling (as a medium)|channel]] Ajysyt, believing that doing so would relieve them of pain during childbirth.<ref name="Loar2010"/> She kept a golden book in which she recorded each one. She is said to have lived on a mountain top in a house with seven stories,<ref name="Loar2010"/> from which she controlled the fate of the world.

==Versions==
The Yakut revere a variety of ajy ({{lang-sah|Айы}}). The primary manifestation, Nelbey Ajyhyt, is responsible for the birth of children; Dzhyësyëgyëy Toyon and Kieng Kieli-Baly Toyon govern the reproduction of horses; Isegey Ajyhyt has responsibility for oxen; and Noruluya manages dogs and foxes. <ref name="Meletinskii">{{cite book|editor=E. M. Meletinskii|title=Mefologicheskii slovar'|date=1990|publisher=Sovetskaya entsiklopediya}}</ref>

When referring to the fertility deity for the births of male animals, such as stallions or bulls, the word ''ajysyt'' is understood to be male. However, when relating to the birth of a mare or cow, the word is feminine.<ref name="Jordan2004">{{cite book|author=Michael Jordan|title=Dictionary of gods and goddesses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aqDC5bwx4_wC&pg=PA10|accessdate=3 January 2012|year=2004|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-5923-2|page=10}}</ref>

==Legends==
One legend recalls how she appeared from the roots of the [[Cosmic Tree]] (alternatively the [[world pillar]] of Yryn-al-tojon)to a pale young man; the tree stood beside a lake of milk. By [[suckling]] the youth she caused his strength to increase a hundredfold.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}

Aisyt was a daughter of Gok-Tengri (Sky-God) and Toprak Ana (Mother Earth) and was viewed with both fear and affection. She represented the night and was pictured as a noble woman. The night's darkness heralded the emergence of malicious spirits from holes.{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}}

==Contemporary representation==

Ajysyt is a featured figure on [[Judy Chicago]]'s installation piece ''[[The Dinner Party]]'', being represented as one of the 999 names on the ''[[List of women in the Heritage Floor|Heritage Floor]].''<ref name="AjysytBM">{{cite web | author= | year=2007 | title=Ajysyt | work=Elizabeth A. Sackler Center for Feminist Art: The Dinner Party: Heritage Floor: Ajysyt | publisher=[[Brooklyn Museum]] | url=http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/eascfa/dinner_party/heritage_floor/ajysyt.php | accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref>

