'''Neopluvial''' is a term referring to a phase of wetter and colder climate in the western United States in the late [[Holocene]],{{sfn|Hockett|2015|p=293}} causing the levels of lakes in the [[Great Basin]] to increase{{sfn|Hockett|2015|p=299}} and previously dry lakes and [[spring (hydrology)|spring]]s to refill.<ref name="Pettigrew1984" /> It is in part correlative to the [[Neoglacial]],{{sfn|Hockett|2015|p=292}} and might have been caused by a change in winter time conditions over the [[North Pacific]].{{sfn|Yuan|Koran|Valdez|2013|p=157}} It resembles the [[pluvial]] period that occurred in western North America during the late [[last glacial maximum]],{{sfn|Yuan|Koran|Valdez|2013|p=158}} but was much weaker than the LGM wet period.{{sfn|Madsen|2000|p=157}}

It has been observed in [[Great Salt Lake]],{{sfn|Madsen|2000|p=157}} [[Fallen Leaf Lake (California)|Fallen Leaf Lake]],<ref name="NobleZimmernann2016" /> [[Lake Cochise]],{{sfn|Yuan|Koran|Valdez|2013|p=155}} the [[Mojave Desert]],<ref name="JonesKlar2007" /> [[Mono Lake]], [[Owens Lake]], [[Pyramid Lake (Nevada)|Pyramid Lake]],<ref name="NobleZimmernann2016" /> [[San Luis Closed Basin|San Luis Lake]],{{sfn|Yuan|Koran|Valdez|2013|p=155}} [[Silver Lake, San Bernardino County, California|Silver Lake]],<ref name="JonesKlar2007" /> [[Summer Lake (Oregon)|Summer Lake]],<ref name="Chewaucan" /> [[Tulare Lake]]<ref name="NegriniWigand2006" /> and [[Walker Lake (Nevada)|Walker Lake]].<ref name="NobleZimmernann2016" />

During the Neopluvial, the Great Salt Lake became fresher,{{sfn|Madsen|2000|p=157}} Pyramid Lake reached a water level of {{convert|1186|m}} above sea level;<ref name="NobleZimmernann2016" /> there is evidence for at least two highstands.{{sfn|Noble|Ball|Zimmerman|Maloney|2016|p=207}} Walker Lake, Owens Lake and Mono Lake experienced their highest Holocene water levels,<ref name="NobleZimmernann2016" /> with the volumes of the latter two lakes more than doubling.<ref name="FutureW" /> Likewise water levels in [[Lake Tahoe]] rose to the point of overflowing into the [[Truckee River]].{{sfn|Noble|Ball|Zimmerman|Maloney|2016|p=206}} Silver Lake in the Mojave Desert formed a perennial lake and vegetation was more widespread in the [[Little Granite Mountains]].<ref name="JonesKlar2007" /> Summer Lake rose above its present-day level to an elevation of {{circa}} {{convert|1278|m}},<ref name="BadgerWatters2004" /> although it was not as high as during the mid-Holocene.<ref name="Chewaucan" /> Water levels rose in Tulare Lake as well.<ref name="NegriniWigand2006" />

In the [[White Mountains (California)|White Mountains]], [[meadow]]s formed during the Neopluvial.<ref name="AbabnehWoolfenden2010" /> [[Glacier]]s grew in the Sierra Nevada,{{sfn|Noble|Ball|Zimmerman|Maloney|2016|p=207}} [[sagebrush]] steppe, [[Ephedra viridis|green Mormon tea]] and other vegetation expanded in the Great Salt Lake region,{{sfn|Madsen|2000|p=161}} [[marsh]]es expanded in the central and northern [[Great Basin]],{{sfn|Hockett|2015|p=292}} [[mammal]] communities in the [[Lake Bonneville]] basin changed,{{sfn|Oviatt|Shroder|2016|p=363-364}} and [[tree line]]s dropped, with the lower limit of wooden vegetation penetrating into deserts.<ref name="WestfallMillar2004" /> Counterintuitively, higher tree line elevations in the [[Lake Bonneville]] area occurred during the Neopluvial.{{sfn|Oviatt|Shroder|2016|p=278}} In the [[Owens Valley]] region, during the Neopluvial the population became more sedentary and trans-[[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] trade became established ("Newberry"/"Middle Archaic Period").<ref name="Ababneh2008" /> Population around [[Alvord Lake (Oregon)|Lake Alvord]] increased during this time and lasted even after the Neopluvial had ended there.<ref name="Pettigrew1984" />

The beginning of the Neopluvial occurred about 6,000 years before present, but did not occur everywhere at the same time. Rising water levels in Lake Tahoe drowned trees between 4,800 and 5,700 years before present.{{sfn|Noble|Ball|Zimmerman|Maloney|2016|p=206}} In the Great Salt Lake, the Neopluvial commenced 5,000 years before present and water levels reached their maximum between 3,000 and 2,000 years before present.{{sfn|Madsen|2000|p=157}} In Pyramid Lake, the Neopluvial commenced starting from 5,000 years [[before present]] and reached a maximum between 4,100 - 3,800 years before present in Pyramid Lake,<ref name="NobleZimmernann2016" /> between 4,000 and 2,000 years before present in the [[Carson Sink]],{{sfn|Noble|Ball|Zimmerman|Maloney|2016|p=207}} between 3,000 - 4,000 years before present in Lake Cochise,{{sfn|Yuan|Koran|Valdez|2013|p=155}} between 5,100 and 2,650 years before present in the central-northern Great Basin,{{sfn|Hockett|2015|p=292}} between 4,000 and 2,500 years before present in the Mojave Desert,<ref name="JonesKlar2007" /> between 4,000 and 1,900 years ago in the Summer Lake area,<ref name="BadgerWatters2004" /> and 3,700 years before present in Fallen Leaf Lake. The end of the Neopluvial in Fallen Leaf Lake occurred 3,650 years before present;<ref name="NobleZimmernann2016" /> after that point precipitation became more irregular until the onset of the [[Little Ice Age]] about 3,000 years later.{{sfn|Noble|Ball|Zimmerman|Maloney|2016|p=208}} In Tulare Lake, the Neopluvial lasted between 4,500 and 2,800 years before present; after that a severe [[drought]] occurred.<ref name="NegriniWigand2006" /> The Neopluvial in the [[Lake Lahontan]] basin ended about 2,000 years ago.<ref name="Pettigrew1984" />

These broadly synchronous patterns in the Great Basin were paralleled in the Rocky Mountains.  High elevation lakes with small watersheds, particularly sensitive to a changing water balance, showed synchronous increase in lake levels from 6,000 to 5,000 years before present, centered at 5,700 years ago. This shift was followed by abundant evidence of [[neoglacial]] cooling throughout the northern hemisphere.  This cooling is primarily explained by steadily declining summer insolation, though synchronous patterns in hydrological responses at sub-millennial scales may be linked to atmospheric circulation shifts driven by factors such as internal variability in ocean-atmosphere teleconnections.{{Sfn|Shuman|Serravezza|2017|p=74}}

The term "neopluvial" has also been used for a mid-to-late Holocene phase of increased moisture noted in the form of increased wetness in eastern [[Texas]], potentially linked to a stronger [[monsoon]].<ref name="WilkinsCurrey1999" />

